TopicTitle: Show off your awesome KSP pictures!

Articles.Content:
The Defenestrator IV

http://i.imgur.com/0x6xVyK.jpg?1?3462

Bored with single missions I set off on a simple premise: To visit and land on every planet and moon not returning to Kerbin or getting resupply until done. An engineering feat, test of skill and planning, resource managing etc, it was and still is a fun project. After a many designs and disasters, this the one that got closest to this mission is the Defenestrator IV. The first 3 went Def 1: Tore itself apart in orbit, 4x antimatter thrusters was too much for it. Def 2: Spontaneous disassemble event while entering warp. Def 3: Complete strut linkage failure on the stitching (big bugs with mods). But this one made it most of the way and is parked in Jool at the halfway mark.

Features: Command pod is also the lander. 4 Parasite dock jr full science probe/landers (reusable return from no/low atmo/grav worlds for science pod processing and refurbishing), 1xUAV parasite vessel for atmo science, 1 Kethane mining unit lander and power generator, 1 remote tug, 1 x 2 seat rover and many other features using the following mods to make this ship reusable and self sustaining. (was once 8xProbe, 2 kethane, 2xUAVs but the part count was too high and frame rate was unplayable)

Mods used:

1: KW rocketry

2: Kerbal attachment system

3: Kethane

4: Interstellar

But I love this shot above of Jool rise over Laythe. This ship just looked good to me had a nice feel, and many hours/days of work to get this ship to look and act the way I wanted. Do give it a shot, make a mother-ship style vessel and attach away, visit all the moons and planets and set yourself the goal of , 1 lander, 1 UAV, 1 rover, several reusable probes, science pod, kethane refueling and have your own Trek through the Kerbin system :3

Awesome! Although you have to admit, KSP Interstellar makes that kind of mission laughably easy compared to attempting it with only stock or stockalike mods.

Go check him out.

I finally had a Kraken attack on one of my probes. Odd part was I wasn't controlling it at the time or anywhere close enough to have physics active on it. I just looked in the tracking station and saw it had split apart. Below was the result...

At the time of the screenshot, it was traveling at 41,521.75 times the speed of light.
Got my mug!

Been spending the greater part of the day designing my All Purpose Exploratory Vehicle. It doubles as both a remotely controlled and manned rover depending on need and has the room for any number of experiments, supplies, etc that conform to its height restriction (no taller than the docking port).

I plan on using it as the basis for my Duna Mobile Exploratory Laboratory (It will be the first thing I've ever put on another planet) as well as a general work vehicle for my Mun colony.

Test runs on Kerbin have proven very promising, as it can maintain its top speed (20m/s IIRC) and turn at those speeds without issue. Has issues with hilly areas (I have to keep it going slow or it will flip over), which I believe my now-installed fully installed RCS thrusters will help compensate for.

PMSR-I: Roving the Mun for 48 years!

Time to bring this poor $deity-forsaken soul back

I've long enjoyed this thread, so it's time to contribute. A friend and I compare KSP missions and designs, but the screenshot function on Linux has a tendency to crash the game, so I've just been snapping shots on my iPhone and uploading them to iCloud. Sometimes the interference is annoying, but occasionally the shot looks more "real" than a screenshot, somehow. Enjoy! https://www.icloud.com/photostream/#A8JtdOXmGa4uOi
